1
00:00:19,980 --> 00:00:24,975
<font color="#7B0000"><i>MyRls.Me</i></font>

2
00:00:28,417 --> 00:00:33,916
♪ ♪ [ Piano ]

3
00:01:19,209 --> 00:01:23,333
[ Boys Imitating Planes Firing ]

4
00:01:33,084 --> 00:01:34,916
[ Imitating Planes Firing ]

5
00:02:01,833 --> 00:02:03,333
[ No Audible Dialogue ]

6
00:02:23,541 --> 00:02:26,540
[ Continuing Imitating Planes ]

7
00:03:01,084 --> 00:03:02,208
Move! Move it!

8
00:03:02,292 --> 00:03:03,332
Move!

9
00:03:04,750 --> 00:03:05,791
Move!

10
00:03:06,125 --> 00:03:07,124
Now!

11
00:03:07,209 --> 00:03:09,666
[ Dog Barking ]

12
00:03:16,583 --> 00:03:18,749
[ Barking ]

13
00:03:33,375 --> 00:03:36,083
[ Imitating Planes ]

14
00:03:37,000 --> 00:03:38,041
It's me home.

15
00:03:38,125 --> 00:03:39,916
Bye, Bruno!
Bye, Bruno!

16
00:04:05,792 --> 00:04:08,791
Hello, sweetheart.
Mum, what's going on?

17
00:04:09,416 --> 00:04:11,707
We're celebrating.
Celebrating?

18
00:04:11,792 --> 00:04:13,707
Your father's been given a promotion.

19
00:04:13,792 --> 00:04:16,290
- That means a better job.
- I know what promotion is.

20
00:04:16,833 --> 00:04:18,707
So we're having a little party to celebrate.

21
00:04:18,792 --> 00:04:21,166
He's still going to be a soldier
though, isn't he?

22
00:04:21,249 --> 00:04:25,083
Yes, my love.
Yes, just a more important one now.

23
00:04:26,084 --> 00:04:27,999
There's some even more exciting news,

24
00:04:28,084 --> 00:04:31,540
but I think Dad wanted
to tell you about that himself.

25
00:04:32,833 --> 00:04:36,749
- Moving? Where to?
- To the countryside.

26
00:04:36,833 --> 00:04:41,540
That's miles away. What about
Karl and Leon and Martin?

27
00:04:41,625 --> 00:04:43,041
Sweetheart, I know it's hard,

28
00:04:43,125 --> 00:04:46,707
but we're all having to say good-bye
to our friends for the time being.

29
00:04:46,792 --> 00:04:49,374
Anyway, we'll make new ones
where we're going. Won't we?

30
00:04:49,458 --> 00:04:51,624
Of course you are.
You'll make lots of new friends.

31
00:04:53,958 --> 00:04:57,624
Bruno, you can have your friends
around in the morning before we go.

32
00:04:57,708 --> 00:05:01,124
[ Dad ]
Think of it as an adventure,
like in one of your books.

33
00:05:02,084 --> 00:05:03,957
But this is the best house ever.

34
00:05:05,084 --> 00:05:08,707
Well, you never know. The house
we're going to might be even better.

35
00:05:08,792 --> 00:05:10,957
Dad says it's got a garden.
Mm-hmm.

36
00:05:12,917 --> 00:05:16,874
Look, the thing is, Bruno,
the thing about being a soldier,

37
00:05:16,958 --> 00:05:20,166
is that life is not so much about choice,
it's more about duty,

38
00:05:20,249 --> 00:05:23,166
so if your country needs you
to go somewhere, you'll go.

39
00:05:23,249 --> 00:05:26,707
Now, of course, going somewhere else
is much easier...

40
00:05:26,792 --> 00:05:30,707
when you know that your family
are so delighted to go with you.

41
00:05:33,416 --> 00:05:36,124
♪ ♪ [ Upbeat ]
[ Laughter]

42
00:05:46,458 --> 00:05:48,999
♪ ♪ [ Continues ]

43
00:06:01,958 --> 00:06:03,916
[ Man Laughing ]

44
00:06:08,166 --> 00:06:10,374
[ No Audible Dialogue ]

45
00:06:12,708 --> 00:06:16,832
Bruno! You're getting bigger
every time I see you.

46
00:06:16,917 --> 00:06:19,123
It's only been a week, Nathalie.

47
00:06:19,208 --> 00:06:22,123
Well, perhaps it's me that's getting smaller.

48
00:06:23,958 --> 00:06:25,540
So, you two,

49
00:06:25,625 --> 00:06:28,791
well, what do you think of all this?
Moving out of Berlin?

50
00:06:28,875 --> 00:06:31,624
Well, Mummy and Daddy say
it's a good thing, so I suppose it must be.

51
00:06:31,708 --> 00:06:33,666
Mmm.

52
00:06:35,458 --> 00:06:39,415
Children, be angels, will you?
Pass some food around.

53
00:06:42,084 --> 00:06:45,499
♪ ♪ [ German Anthem ]
[ Applause ]

54
00:06:45,625 --> 00:06:47,749
Heil Hitler!
Heil Hitler!

55
00:06:49,708 --> 00:06:52,457
[ Applause Continues ]

56
00:07:12,625 --> 00:07:15,832
♪ ♪ [ Anthem Stops ]

57
00:07:15,917 --> 00:07:18,749
[ Chattering ]

58
00:07:18,875 --> 00:07:22,707
♪ ♪ [ Upbeat Clarinet ]
[ No Audible Dialogue ]

59
00:07:22,792 --> 00:07:24,248
Congratulations.

60
00:07:25,708 --> 00:07:29,123
Doesn't he look wonderful?
Absolutely.

61
00:07:29,958 --> 00:07:32,290
I'm so proud of you, my boy.

62
00:07:33,042 --> 00:07:37,207
Oh, dear. I sometimes wonder
if this is all down to me,

63
00:07:37,291 --> 00:07:41,165
making you those costumes
for your little plays when you were tiny.

64
00:07:41,249 --> 00:07:45,374
- You used to adore all that dressing up.
- Nathalie.

65
00:07:45,458 --> 00:07:48,415
Does it still make you feel special, Ralf dear?

66
00:07:49,291 --> 00:07:52,374
The uniform and what it stands for?

67
00:07:52,458 --> 00:07:55,957
Mother, it's a party.
Let's not spoil things.

68
00:07:56,041 --> 00:07:58,624
[ Chuckles ]
Me, spoil things?

69
00:08:00,291 --> 00:08:02,123
You should be careful.

70
00:08:02,208 --> 00:08:06,165
Airing your views so publicly
could land you in trouble.
You know that.

71
00:08:06,249 --> 00:08:07,999
[ Scoffs ]

72
00:08:09,041 --> 00:08:12,332
So, how long are we losing you for, my boy?

73
00:08:12,458 --> 00:08:17,499
Until the war is won,
I would think.
Well, not so long then.

74
00:08:19,291 --> 00:08:25,624
♪ ♪ [ Man Singing ]
♪ You've got to smile
when you say good-bye ♪

75
00:08:25,708 --> 00:08:31,082
♪ You've got to smile as the days go by ♪

76
00:08:31,166 --> 00:08:37,290
♪ And all the time that you're away
I'm thinking of you ♪

77
00:08:37,375 --> 00:08:42,165
♪ I'll write and say from day to day
how much I love you ♪

78
00:08:42,291 --> 00:08:48,540
[ Indistinct ]
♪ You've got to smile
when you say good-bye ♪

79
00:08:48,625 --> 00:08:54,415
♪ You've got to smile till the clouds roll by ♪

80
00:08:54,500 --> 00:09:00,040
♪ So till we meet again
Say cheerio and then ♪

81
00:09:00,124 --> 00:09:05,624
♪ Give me a smile
when you say good-bye ♪

82
00:09:06,792 --> 00:09:08,374
♪ ♪ [ Continues ]
[ Laughing ]

83
00:09:08,458 --> 00:09:10,582
[ Imitates Gun Cocking, Firing ]

84
00:09:10,667 --> 00:09:15,123
[ Boys Laughing, Imitating Gunfire ]

85
00:09:26,208 --> 00:09:27,457
[ Mother ]
Bruno!

86
00:09:29,249 --> 00:09:31,956
♪ ♪ [ Fades ]

87
00:09:32,875 --> 00:09:36,207
All right, Bruno.
Time to say good-bye.

88
00:10:03,792 --> 00:10:05,707
Bye-bye.
Bye-bye!

89
00:10:06,792 --> 00:10:08,624
[ Imitating Planes ]

90
00:10:15,583 --> 00:10:17,791
[ Imitating Gunfire ]

91
00:10:40,708 --> 00:10:44,540
[ Girl ]
"Time has come for me to sleep
Lord, I thank Thee for Thy keep

92
00:10:44,625 --> 00:10:48,040
Watch this night well over me
And teach me, Lord, to trust in Thee

93
00:10:48,124 --> 00:10:51,540
Care for children, sick and poor
Grant them, Lord, Thy blessing more

94
00:10:51,625 --> 00:10:55,123
And this I pray in Jesus' name
Care for my family just the same"

95
00:10:55,208 --> 00:10:56,248
Amen.

96
00:11:02,124 --> 00:11:05,540
[ Train Whistle Blows ]

97
00:11:40,874 --> 00:11:45,040
Children, look.
Look! Our new home.

98
00:12:34,041 --> 00:12:37,707
I have some business to take care of.
I'll see you shortly.

99
00:12:54,541 --> 00:12:56,540
Well, what do we think?

100
00:12:59,458 --> 00:13:01,540
Oh, come on. It's lovely.

101
00:13:01,625 --> 00:13:05,082
You two choose your rooms.
I'll have Maria come...

102
00:13:06,708 --> 00:13:08,624
and help you unpack.

103
00:13:22,791 --> 00:13:26,290
What do you think of it, Maria?
The new house.

104
00:13:27,375 --> 00:13:31,374
Well, it's not for me to say.

105
00:13:33,375 --> 00:13:36,499
But it won't feel like home
until we make it feel like home, will it?

106
00:13:36,583 --> 00:13:39,499
[ Footsteps Approach ]

107
00:13:44,083 --> 00:13:45,956
[ Man ]
Is he already up?

108
00:13:50,957 --> 00:13:52,457
[ Whispers ]
Who was that?

109
00:13:52,541 --> 00:13:55,165
[ Whispers ]
One of your father's soldiers,
I suppose.

110
00:13:55,249 --> 00:13:59,624
- He looked very serious.
- Well, they are, aren't they?

111
00:14:03,458 --> 00:14:08,415
- Why are we whispering?
- I don't know.
[ Giggles ]

112
00:14:42,957 --> 00:14:46,790
- [ Mother] And play with who?
- The children over on the farm.

113
00:14:46,874 --> 00:14:49,873
Farm? I didn't see a farm.
And that one, too.

114
00:14:49,957 --> 00:14:52,290
You can only see it from my room.

115
00:14:52,375 --> 00:14:54,665
Hmm.
And are some children there?

116
00:14:54,791 --> 00:14:57,540
Yes, quite a few.
That's good.

117
00:14:57,666 --> 00:15:01,415
So, I'll be able to play with them.
I don't see why not.

118
00:15:01,500 --> 00:15:05,748
I'll wait a little bit,
just to see what they're like,

119
00:15:05,874 --> 00:15:09,123
because they look a bit strange.
The children do?

120
00:15:09,874 --> 00:15:12,540
Well, and the farmers.
What sort of strange?

121
00:15:12,624 --> 00:15:14,831
[ Door Opens ]

122
00:15:17,707 --> 00:15:19,290
I'm sorry.

123
00:15:20,124 --> 00:15:21,123
Vegetables.

124
00:15:22,916 --> 00:15:24,123
There.

125
00:15:28,582 --> 00:15:29,915
Bruno, have you unpacked everything?

126
00:15:29,999 --> 00:15:32,998
Because I think you should
go back upstairs and finish off.

127
00:15:36,083 --> 00:15:37,748
Thank you, ma'am.

128
00:15:41,749 --> 00:15:43,123
Bruno.

129
00:15:43,749 --> 00:15:45,998
- I told you they were strange.
- Who?

130
00:15:46,083 --> 00:15:48,748
The farmers. They wear pajamas.

131
00:15:57,124 --> 00:16:01,457
[ Footsteps ]

132
00:16:06,375 --> 00:16:08,915
Bruno, I was just coming to look for you.

133
00:16:09,540 --> 00:16:11,499
Well, thank you for that.
That was extremely useful.

134
00:16:11,624 --> 00:16:13,790
I'll be over to see you later.
Of course, Herr Kommandant.

135
00:16:15,375 --> 00:16:16,748
Come in.

136
00:16:21,208 --> 00:16:22,956
Sit down, sit down.

137
00:16:24,124 --> 00:16:26,123
Well, what do you think?

138
00:16:28,208 --> 00:16:29,457
Oh, dear.

139
00:16:30,124 --> 00:16:31,790
I want to go home.

140
00:16:33,624 --> 00:16:37,539
You are home, Bruno.
Home is where the family is.

141
00:16:37,624 --> 00:16:39,290
Isn't that right?

142
00:16:41,375 --> 00:16:45,498
Bruno, you have to at least
give the place a chance.

143
00:16:45,582 --> 00:16:47,207
I promise you,
it won't be long before you-

144
00:16:47,291 --> 00:16:52,332
Why do the farmers wear pajamas?
I can see them from my window.

145
00:17:00,874 --> 00:17:05,290
The thing is, Bruno, those people-

146
00:17:06,083 --> 00:17:09,248
Well, you see, they're not really people at all.

147
00:17:14,375 --> 00:17:16,123
Bruno, who told you it was a farm?

148
00:17:16,208 --> 00:17:17,956
Was it Maria?
No.

149
00:17:18,624 --> 00:17:20,248
It is a farm, isn't it?

150
00:17:22,208 --> 00:17:22,956
[ Mother ]
Yes.

151
00:17:25,540 --> 00:17:27,998
[ Bruno ]
Is it to do with your new job?

152
00:17:28,083 --> 00:17:30,831
All you need to know about my work here, Bruno,

153
00:17:30,916 --> 00:17:34,665
is that it's very important
to our country and to you.

154
00:17:35,540 --> 00:17:37,873
We're working very hard
to make this world a better place...

155
00:17:37,957 --> 00:17:38,956
for you to grow up in.

156
00:17:39,041 --> 00:17:41,790
But you're not a farmer.
You're a soldier.

157
00:17:42,457 --> 00:17:45,498
Bruno, can you come and help me
finish sorting out in the kitchen?

158
00:17:45,582 --> 00:17:49,456
I can still play with them, though?
The children.

159
00:17:50,375 --> 00:17:52,706
I don't think so,
Bruno. No.

160
00:17:52,791 --> 00:17:56,332
Like you say, they're a bit strange.
A bit-

161
00:17:56,416 --> 00:17:58,374
Well, they're different.

162
00:17:58,957 --> 00:18:01,623
Don't worry, my darling.
We'll find you some new friends,

163
00:18:01,707 --> 00:18:04,415
but they won't be the ones from the farm.

164
00:18:04,916 --> 00:18:08,248
Ralf, you promised.
You said it was miles away.
It is.

165
00:18:08,333 --> 00:18:10,873
How was I to know he could see it
from the bedroom window?

166
00:18:10,957 --> 00:18:12,456
There was one of them in our kitchen.

167
00:18:14,124 --> 00:18:15,332
[ Sighs ]

168
00:18:37,624 --> 00:18:39,873
[ Clicks Tongue, Sighs ]

169
00:18:43,083 --> 00:18:44,623
[ Chuckles ]

170
00:18:54,957 --> 00:18:57,748
[ Maria ]
Master Bruno, how are you today?
Fed up.

171
00:18:59,208 --> 00:19:02,123
You said the same thing
every day for two whole weeks.

172
00:19:02,208 --> 00:19:05,207
- It's true.
- Well, you should be out playing.

173
00:19:05,291 --> 00:19:07,831
- Playing with who?
- I don't know. Gretel?

174
00:19:09,791 --> 00:19:14,665
- Well, you can make your own fun.
- That's what I'm trying to do.

175
00:19:14,749 --> 00:19:15,956
One thing's for sure,

176
00:19:16,041 --> 00:19:19,790
sitting around being miserable
won't make things any happier.

177
00:19:21,666 --> 00:19:25,956
[ Bruno Imitating Plane Firing ]

178
00:20:12,041 --> 00:20:14,873
- Bruno, what are you doing?
- Exploring!

179
00:20:14,957 --> 00:20:18,165
No! No, not in the back.
I told you, it's out of bounds.

180
00:20:18,249 --> 00:20:20,790
- Explore at the front.
- But I've explored it all.

181
00:20:20,874 --> 00:20:24,082
- Well, find something else to do.
- Like what?

182
00:20:25,083 --> 00:20:28,207
Come back in now, and we'll think of something.

183
00:20:33,582 --> 00:20:37,207
♪ ♪ [ March ]

184
00:20:37,290 --> 00:20:42,165
♪ ♪ [ Slow Orchestral ]

185
00:20:56,624 --> 00:20:58,289
So, children, what are you doing today?

186
00:20:58,415 --> 00:21:00,706
Same as yesterday.
And what was that?

187
00:21:00,791 --> 00:21:04,247
- Same as the day before.
- Except you went exploring.

188
00:21:05,624 --> 00:21:08,165
- I like exploring.
- Where did you go?

189
00:21:08,248 --> 00:21:12,082
I wanted to look in the back garden,
but Mum wouldn't let me.

190
00:21:12,166 --> 00:21:13,498
The back garden?

191
00:21:14,582 --> 00:21:16,123
Well, God forbid.

192
00:21:16,208 --> 00:21:18,414
I expect you'll be missing
those friends of yours.

193
00:21:18,540 --> 00:21:20,956
I even miss school.
[ Chuckles ]

194
00:21:21,874 --> 00:21:24,790
Well, I never thought I'd hear you say that.

195
00:21:24,916 --> 00:21:26,831
Anyway, you won't be missing it
for long.
Really?

196
00:21:26,916 --> 00:21:29,998
I've arranged a tutor for you both.

197
00:21:30,791 --> 00:21:33,623
A Herr Liszt will be visiting twice a week.

198
00:21:34,457 --> 00:21:37,206
[ Bruno ]
So we're not going to school?

199
00:21:39,415 --> 00:21:41,289
School's coming here?
Mm-hmm.

200
00:21:42,124 --> 00:21:44,581
On an old bicycle, I gather.

201
00:22:02,791 --> 00:22:05,040
It's a bird without the-

202
00:22:06,041 --> 00:22:08,289
[ Giggles ]

203
00:22:29,290 --> 00:22:30,206
[ Sighs ]

204
00:22:30,290 --> 00:22:33,539
Good morning, little man.
And how are you this morning?

205
00:22:34,290 --> 00:22:37,373
Can I ask you a favor?
Well, you can ask.

206
00:22:38,791 --> 00:22:41,373
Are there any spare tires around?

207
00:22:41,457 --> 00:22:43,915
An old one from one of the trucks or something?

208
00:22:43,999 --> 00:22:46,831
Well, the only spare tire
I've seen around here...

209
00:22:46,916 --> 00:22:48,456
belongs to Lieutenant Meinberg.

210
00:22:48,540 --> 00:22:50,123
[ Gretel Giggles ]

211
00:22:55,041 --> 00:22:58,456
Well, is he using it?
Yes, he's very attached to it.

212
00:22:59,248 --> 00:23:02,206
Stop it. He doesn't understand.
He's only eight.

213
00:23:02,290 --> 00:23:05,790
You're only 12,
so stop pretending you're any older.

214
00:23:07,957 --> 00:23:09,831
What do you want a tire for, anyway?

215
00:23:09,916 --> 00:23:12,873
- I want to make a swing.
- A swing?

216
00:23:12,957 --> 00:23:14,956
That does sound exciting.

217
00:23:21,499 --> 00:23:22,498
You!

218
00:23:23,916 --> 00:23:25,122
Here, now.

219
00:23:27,832 --> 00:23:29,164
Move!

220
00:23:31,749 --> 00:23:34,247
Take this boy to the outhouse
in the back garden.

221
00:23:35,248 --> 00:23:37,289
There are some tires in there.
He will select one.

222
00:23:37,374 --> 00:23:39,623
You will carry it where he asks.
Do you understand?

223
00:23:44,791 --> 00:23:46,956
Well, little man, what are you waiting for?

224
00:24:31,332 --> 00:24:33,164
How about this one?

225
00:25:01,040 --> 00:25:02,331
[ Shouts ]

226
00:25:20,165 --> 00:25:22,206
Where's my mum?

227
00:25:24,082 --> 00:25:25,289
She's out.

228
00:25:26,207 --> 00:25:28,706
When is she back?
Soon, I expect.

229
00:25:29,998 --> 00:25:31,623
But don't worry.

230
00:25:33,499 --> 00:25:36,915
But I might bleed to death.
No, you won't.

231
00:25:43,956 --> 00:25:48,955
Will I need to go to hospital?
No. It's only a small cut.

232
00:25:50,248 --> 00:25:51,873
[ Inhales ]

233
00:25:51,956 --> 00:25:54,122
Oh, come on. It's not that bad.

234
00:25:54,998 --> 00:25:58,331
There, all better.

235
00:26:10,582 --> 00:26:13,997
- What's your name?
- Pavel.

236
00:26:15,998 --> 00:26:19,164
Now, you better sit still for a few minutes...

237
00:26:19,582 --> 00:26:22,247
before you start walking around on that again.

238
00:26:22,332 --> 00:26:24,414
Will you tell my mum what happened?

239
00:26:25,956 --> 00:26:28,790
I think she's going to see it for herself.

240
00:26:29,832 --> 00:26:32,331
She'll probably want to take me to a doctor.

241
00:26:33,707 --> 00:26:35,414
I don't think so.

242
00:26:35,540 --> 00:26:38,706
It could be worse than it looks.
It isn't.

243
00:26:39,832 --> 00:26:42,665
How would you know?
You're not a doctor.

244
00:26:47,123 --> 00:26:50,122
- Yes, I am.
- No, you're not.

245
00:26:50,207 --> 00:26:51,498
You peel potatoes.

246
00:26:53,374 --> 00:26:55,456
I practiced as a doctor.

247
00:26:56,624 --> 00:26:58,289
Before I-

248
00:26:58,374 --> 00:27:00,456
Before I came here.

249
00:27:01,540 --> 00:27:05,414
You couldn't have been much good
then, if you had to practice.

250
00:27:07,666 --> 00:27:09,914
[ Chuckles Quietly ]

251
00:27:13,956 --> 00:27:18,581
Now, what are you going to be when you grow up?

252
00:27:19,624 --> 00:27:22,790
I know. An explorer.

253
00:27:23,457 --> 00:27:24,748
How do you know that?

254
00:27:28,582 --> 00:27:29,790
Is it nice on the farm?

255
00:27:39,374 --> 00:27:41,997
Bruno. Bruno,
what happened to you?

256
00:27:42,082 --> 00:27:45,831
I made a swing,
but I fell off it and cut my knee.

257
00:27:45,915 --> 00:27:49,539
But Pavel here, he carried me in
and put a bandage on it.

258
00:27:56,749 --> 00:27:58,748
Go to your room.
But Pavel says I-

259
00:27:58,831 --> 00:28:00,997
Don't argue. Go to your room.

260
00:28:29,123 --> 00:28:30,456
Thank you.

261
00:28:51,040 --> 00:28:54,164
♪ ♪ [ Upbeat Orchestra ]

262
00:28:54,873 --> 00:28:57,498
It's not fair, you having this view.

263
00:28:57,582 --> 00:28:59,414
Well, I'm not swapping.

264
00:28:59,499 --> 00:29:01,456
[ Bell Rings ]

265
00:29:04,582 --> 00:29:06,498
I think school's here.

266
00:29:08,248 --> 00:29:10,456
[ Man ]
No, I mean more recent history.

267
00:29:10,582 --> 00:29:14,331
Are you interested in current affairs?
Yes, very.

268
00:29:14,415 --> 00:29:18,164
So, you'll be aware of the situation...

269
00:29:18,248 --> 00:29:20,164
in which our great nation
presently finds itself.

270
00:29:20,707 --> 00:29:25,039
Yes. I read newspapers whenever I can
and one of Father's men...

271
00:29:25,123 --> 00:29:27,122
keeps me up to date
on everything that's happening.

272
00:29:27,207 --> 00:29:31,789
[ Man ]
Good. And you, Bruno.
Have you been reading newspapers?

273
00:29:33,582 --> 00:29:37,247
- Have you been reading anything?
- Books.

274
00:29:37,998 --> 00:29:40,331
Good. What sort of books?

275
00:29:41,457 --> 00:29:43,331
Adventure books, mainly.

276
00:29:43,415 --> 00:29:48,498
You know, knights in shining armor,
exploring strange lands and stuff,

277
00:29:48,582 --> 00:29:51,247
and silly princesses always getting in the way.

278
00:29:51,332 --> 00:29:55,747
Well, this is why I'm here to help.
You're how old now, Bruno? Eight?

279
00:29:56,956 --> 00:29:58,830
Time to get your head
out of those fiction books...

280
00:29:58,915 --> 00:30:00,997
and start learning about fact.

281
00:30:01,082 --> 00:30:05,039
Time, I think,
to turn your mind to the real world,

282
00:30:05,123 --> 00:30:07,789
and I believe this would be the perfect start.

283
00:31:23,706 --> 00:31:25,581
[ Neighing ]

284
00:31:43,748 --> 00:31:45,164
Die, die!

285
00:31:56,207 --> 00:31:58,373
Die, die.

286
00:32:51,956 --> 00:32:53,122
Hello.

287
00:32:54,290 --> 00:32:55,914
[ Gasps ]

288
00:32:59,165 --> 00:33:00,705
I'm exploring.

289
00:33:06,415 --> 00:33:09,997
- What are you doing?
- We're-We're building a new hut.

290
00:33:16,123 --> 00:33:18,914
[ Bruno ]
Have you got
lots of friends over there?

291
00:33:19,790 --> 00:33:22,914
A few. But we fight a lot.

292
00:33:22,998 --> 00:33:27,622
That's why I like being out here.
I can be on my own.

293
00:33:30,123 --> 00:33:32,830
- I'm Bruno.
- Shmuel.

294
00:33:33,415 --> 00:33:35,456
Sorry?
I'm Shmuel.

295
00:33:37,082 --> 00:33:40,914
That's your name? Never heard
of anyone called that before.

296
00:33:40,998 --> 00:33:43,206
I've never heard of anyone called Bruno.

297
00:33:43,290 --> 00:33:47,664
But Shmuel.
No one's called Shmuel.

298
00:33:53,123 --> 00:33:55,456
I live in the house, back there.

299
00:33:58,623 --> 00:34:01,456
Have you got any food on you?
No.

300
00:34:02,873 --> 00:34:04,414
- Are you hungry?
- Mmm.

301
00:34:13,623 --> 00:34:15,247
How old are you?

302
00:34:15,998 --> 00:34:18,331
- Eight.
- Me, too!

303
00:34:24,623 --> 00:34:28,289
It's not fair,
me being stuck over here on my own,

304
00:34:28,374 --> 00:34:30,872
while you're over there,
playing with friends all day.

305
00:34:30,956 --> 00:34:34,164
- Playing?
- Well, that number.

306
00:34:34,498 --> 00:34:37,914
Isn't it a part of
a game or something?
It's just my number.

307
00:34:37,998 --> 00:34:40,373
Everyone gets given a different number.

308
00:34:40,456 --> 00:34:42,414
Right. Then what happens?

309
00:34:42,498 --> 00:34:45,830
[ Whistle Blows ]
[ Gasps ]

310
00:34:45,915 --> 00:34:48,373
- I have to go back now!
- Really?

311
00:34:48,456 --> 00:34:49,497
Yeah.

312
00:34:50,123 --> 00:34:53,039
It was nice to meet you, Shmuel.

313
00:34:53,123 --> 00:34:55,413
And you, Bruno.

314
00:34:57,414 --> 00:34:58,622
Come back!

315
00:35:06,165 --> 00:35:07,289
Bye.

316
00:35:18,998 --> 00:35:21,289
Mum, I can't find my football.

317
00:35:21,374 --> 00:35:23,122
Well, it'll be in one of your cupboards, sweet.

318
00:35:23,665 --> 00:35:24,955
It isn't. I've looked.

319
00:35:25,998 --> 00:35:27,830
Can I have a piece of chocolate?

320
00:35:28,623 --> 00:35:30,122
Mmm. A piece. Yes.

321
00:35:33,831 --> 00:35:35,872
[ Door Squeaks ]

322
00:35:37,623 --> 00:35:39,164
Bruno?

323
00:35:39,248 --> 00:35:43,247
- Have you looked in the cellar?
- The cellar?

324
00:35:43,332 --> 00:35:46,664
- For your football.
- Oh.

325
00:36:24,623 --> 00:36:25,747
Damn.

326
00:36:51,831 --> 00:36:55,288
- Gretel, I've just seen all your-
- All my what?

327
00:36:56,414 --> 00:36:59,580
All your dolls, down in the cellar.

328
00:37:00,456 --> 00:37:03,580
Dolls are for little girls.

329
00:37:03,665 --> 00:37:06,330
It's not right to be playing with silly toys...

330
00:37:06,414 --> 00:37:09,664
while people are away
risking their lives for the Fatherland.

331
00:37:17,331 --> 00:37:20,455
[ Whistle Blows ]

332
00:37:35,040 --> 00:37:37,246
[ Whistle Blows ]

333
00:37:44,706 --> 00:37:47,081
[ Electricity Buzzes ]

334
00:37:50,915 --> 00:37:55,164
"My people's density is my density."
Destiny.

335
00:37:57,706 --> 00:38:01,413
"Its struggles and its sorrows,
its joys and its miseries are mine.

336
00:38:01,498 --> 00:38:05,122
"I must work and create
for the resurrection of my Fatherland.

337
00:38:05,207 --> 00:38:07,789
"The history of my people
is great and glorious."

338
00:38:07,873 --> 00:38:09,372
And it's 12:00.

339
00:38:12,456 --> 00:38:15,747
- I'm sorry?
- Isn't that when we finish?

340
00:38:16,665 --> 00:38:19,830
The termination of the lesson
is for the tutor to decide, Bruno,

341
00:38:19,915 --> 00:38:22,830
not the pupil.
Now, will you please continue?

342
00:38:38,040 --> 00:38:39,872
Bruno, there you are.

343
00:38:40,831 --> 00:38:44,205
I'm just going into town for an hour.
Do you want to come?

344
00:38:46,498 --> 00:38:47,789
You be careful on that thing.

345
00:38:49,040 --> 00:38:51,081
Thank you.
[ Doors Close ]

346
00:38:53,123 --> 00:38:55,455
[ Engine Starts ]

347
00:39:08,498 --> 00:39:10,705
[ Bruno ]
Can I ask you something?

348
00:39:10,790 --> 00:39:13,497
Why do you people wear pajamas all day?

349
00:39:14,164 --> 00:39:17,830
- They're not pajamas.
- Well, those.

350
00:39:18,373 --> 00:39:21,413
We have to. They took
all our other clothes away.

351
00:39:21,498 --> 00:39:23,330
Who did?
The soldiers.

352
00:39:23,414 --> 00:39:25,081
The soldiers? Why?

353
00:39:28,082 --> 00:39:31,081
I don't like soldiers. Do you?

354
00:39:31,748 --> 00:39:34,872
I do, quite.
My dad's a soldier,

355
00:39:35,539 --> 00:39:38,121
but not the sort that takes
people's clothes away for no reason.

356
00:39:38,915 --> 00:39:40,497
What sort, then?

357
00:39:42,331 --> 00:39:45,039
Well, he's the important sort.

358
00:39:45,122 --> 00:39:48,580
He's in charge of making
everything better for everyone.

359
00:39:50,623 --> 00:39:54,538
- So is your dad a farmer?
- No, he's a watchmaker.

360
00:39:56,122 --> 00:40:00,372
Or was. Most of the time now,
he just mends boots.

361
00:40:03,289 --> 00:40:05,455
It's funny how grown-ups
can't make their minds up...

362
00:40:05,539 --> 00:40:08,622
about what they want to do.
It's like Pavel.

363
00:40:08,706 --> 00:40:11,163
Do you know him?
Lives over there.

364
00:40:12,623 --> 00:40:17,330
He used to be a doctor,
but gave it all up to peel potatoes.

365
00:40:26,956 --> 00:40:28,497
[ Bruno ]
Can I ask you another question?

366
00:40:28,581 --> 00:40:31,163
What do you burn in those chimneys?

367
00:40:31,247 --> 00:40:34,914
I saw them going the other day.
Is it just lots of hay and stuff?

368
00:40:34,998 --> 00:40:38,039
I don't know.
We're not allowed over there.

369
00:40:38,122 --> 00:40:39,789
Mama says it's old clothes.

370
00:40:40,414 --> 00:40:42,914
Well, whatever it is, it smells horrid.

371
00:40:42,998 --> 00:40:44,789
[ Giggles ]

372
00:40:44,873 --> 00:40:46,372
[ Sighs ]

373
00:40:46,456 --> 00:40:48,622
I wish you'd remembered the chocolate.

374
00:40:48,706 --> 00:40:50,330
Yes, I'm sorry.

375
00:40:50,414 --> 00:40:53,163
I know! Perhaps you can come
and have supper with us sometime.

376
00:40:53,247 --> 00:40:56,039
I can't, can I? Because of this.

377
00:40:56,790 --> 00:40:59,288
But that's to stop
the animals getting out, isn't it?

378
00:40:59,373 --> 00:41:02,872
Animals?
No, it's to stop people getting out.

379
00:41:02,956 --> 00:41:05,121
Are you not allowed out?

380
00:41:06,081 --> 00:41:10,163
- Why? What have you done?
- I'm a Jew.

381
00:41:22,790 --> 00:41:24,455
I think I should go now.

382
00:41:29,748 --> 00:41:32,246
Will you be here tomorrow?
I'll try.

383
00:41:32,331 --> 00:41:34,997
Good-bye, then!
Bye.

384
00:41:36,039 --> 00:41:38,747
♪ ♪ [ Singing In German ]
[ Knocks On Door ]

385
00:41:39,456 --> 00:41:41,538
Little present, sweetheart.

386
00:41:45,122 --> 00:41:46,789
Thank you, Mummy.

387
00:41:54,706 --> 00:41:57,622
- Have you seen Bruno?
- Outside on his swing, I think.

388
00:42:11,706 --> 00:42:15,372
Yes, Thursday's perfect.
I'll have a car come to collect you both.

389
00:42:15,456 --> 00:42:16,914
Are Grandma and Grandpa coming?

390
00:42:18,790 --> 00:42:22,330
Hey, did you smell that
horrible smell the other day?

391
00:42:22,414 --> 00:42:25,330
- Coming from the chimneys.
- What sort of ill?

392
00:42:27,122 --> 00:42:29,288
The day I fell off the swing.

393
00:42:29,997 --> 00:42:32,747
Did you smell it, Mum?
Father.

394
00:42:32,831 --> 00:42:34,205
Mum.

395
00:42:35,997 --> 00:42:37,705
Let me speak to her.

396
00:42:37,790 --> 00:42:39,705
Yes, she is. I can hear her.

397
00:42:43,122 --> 00:42:45,455
Yes. We look forward to it.
Good-bye.

398
00:42:48,456 --> 00:42:49,789
[ Sighs ]

399
00:42:51,247 --> 00:42:53,622
Is Grandma not coming?
No.

400
00:42:54,122 --> 00:42:57,622
She's poorly, apparently, but Grandpa's coming.

401
00:42:59,790 --> 00:43:01,914
- Did you smell it, Dad?
- What?

402
00:43:01,997 --> 00:43:05,497
That horrid smell from the chimneys.
What is it?

403
00:43:09,247 --> 00:43:11,538
I think they just burn rubbish there sometimes.

404
00:43:11,623 --> 00:43:13,330
Look.
What?

405
00:43:16,539 --> 00:43:17,913
Hey!
Gretel.

406
00:43:18,665 --> 00:43:19,413
[ Chuckles ]

407
00:43:19,498 --> 00:43:21,080
Hey, that's not fair!

408
00:43:21,164 --> 00:43:22,622
- Gretel.
- What?

409
00:43:23,539 --> 00:43:25,163
It's only a game.

410
00:43:30,539 --> 00:43:33,038
Ralf, this tutor you brought in,

411
00:43:33,122 --> 00:43:36,872
does he usually teach children
as young as Gretel and Bruno?

412
00:43:37,498 --> 00:43:39,121
I believe so. Why?

413
00:43:39,206 --> 00:43:41,121
Well, do we know what he's teaching them?

414
00:43:41,206 --> 00:43:43,038
Gretel seems to have
become so-

415
00:43:43,122 --> 00:43:45,664
They're being taught what all children
are being taught at the moment.

416
00:43:45,748 --> 00:43:47,497
They mustn't get left behind.

417
00:43:48,914 --> 00:43:50,954
Come on.
[ Kisses ]

418
00:43:51,790 --> 00:43:52,830
Let's get to bed.

419
00:44:04,456 --> 00:44:07,163
"The Jew slandered us and incited our enemies.

420
00:44:07,247 --> 00:44:09,622
The Jew corrupted us through bad books.

421
00:44:09,706 --> 00:44:11,705
He mocked our literature and our music.

422
00:44:11,790 --> 00:44:14,205
Everywhere, his influence was destructive,

423
00:44:14,289 --> 00:44:17,413
the eventual result of which
was our nation's collapse,

424
00:44:17,539 --> 00:44:19,121
and then-"
Yes, Bruno?

425
00:44:19,872 --> 00:44:22,121
I don't understand.

426
00:44:22,206 --> 00:44:24,747
A nation's collapse is all down to this one man?

427
00:44:25,289 --> 00:44:28,789
The Jew here means the entire Jewish race.

428
00:44:28,872 --> 00:44:30,829
If it had been just one man,

429
00:44:30,914 --> 00:44:33,580
I'm sure something would've been done about him.

430
00:44:35,623 --> 00:44:38,789
There is such a thing as a nice Jew,
though, isn't there?

431
00:44:38,872 --> 00:44:42,622
I think, Bruno, if you ever found a nice Jew,

432
00:44:43,790 --> 00:44:46,829
you would be the best explorer in the world.

433
00:44:51,039 --> 00:44:52,664
Continue, Gretel.

434
00:44:54,623 --> 00:44:57,705
"The aim of the Jew
is to become the ruler of humanity.

435
00:44:57,790 --> 00:45:00,455
The Jew is not creative, but destructive.

436
00:45:00,539 --> 00:45:02,954
He is the enemy of culture.

437
00:45:03,039 --> 00:45:06,372
Thousands of Germans
have been made poor by the Jew."

438
00:45:09,331 --> 00:45:14,788
[ Plane Engines Humming ]

439
00:45:19,706 --> 00:45:21,205
Master Bruno.

440
00:45:22,164 --> 00:45:25,788
What are you doing? You've just
had your lunch, haven't you?

441
00:45:25,872 --> 00:45:29,705
I was going for a walk,
and I thought I might get peckish.

442
00:45:29,789 --> 00:45:32,788
But don't make a mess of
your satchel. Bring it here.

443
00:45:32,872 --> 00:45:37,163
- I'll wrap it properly for you.
- No. It's none of your business.

444
00:45:37,247 --> 00:45:38,954
Bruno, what is it?

445
00:45:39,830 --> 00:45:42,246
What are you doing with your satchel?

446
00:45:42,331 --> 00:45:46,954
Herr Liszt gave us some books.
I'm going out on the swing to read.

447
00:45:48,456 --> 00:45:50,538
- Let me see.
- What?

448
00:45:50,623 --> 00:45:53,330
The books.
No.

449
00:45:53,414 --> 00:45:56,622
Bruno, I just want to see
what books Herr Liszt has given you.

450
00:45:58,539 --> 00:46:00,413
I told a lie.
What?

451
00:46:01,789 --> 00:46:03,288
I've just got...

452
00:46:05,914 --> 00:46:07,497
adventure books.

453
00:46:14,456 --> 00:46:15,746
[ Chuckles ]

454
00:46:15,830 --> 00:46:18,080
Go on. Off you go, then.

455
00:46:21,747 --> 00:46:24,038
[ Mother ]
Now, Maria,
there's two extra for supper tonight.

456
00:46:24,122 --> 00:46:25,288
The Kommandant's father will be here,

457
00:46:25,373 --> 00:46:27,705
and I believe Lieutenant Kotler is joining us.

458
00:46:50,539 --> 00:46:51,664
Here.

459
00:47:03,122 --> 00:47:04,788
What's the matter?

460
00:47:07,331 --> 00:47:09,996
- Don't throw it back.
- What? Why not?

461
00:47:11,747 --> 00:47:13,829
- It's dangerous.
- Dangerous?

462
00:47:13,914 --> 00:47:15,497
It's just a ball. Come on.

463
00:47:19,581 --> 00:47:20,788
Do you not like playing?

464
00:47:25,039 --> 00:47:27,788
- Just not ball games?
- Not here.

465
00:47:32,997 --> 00:47:34,746
Tell me how the number game works.

466
00:47:34,830 --> 00:47:37,497
I told you, it's not a game.
We just all have numbers.

467
00:47:37,581 --> 00:47:39,455
[ Whistle Blows ]
[ Man Yelling ]

468
00:47:45,498 --> 00:47:46,954
Shmuel!

469
00:48:00,747 --> 00:48:02,788
Bruno! What are you doing?

470
00:48:04,539 --> 00:48:07,663
My ball went over.
I was just getting it back.

471
00:48:13,456 --> 00:48:15,330
[ Exhales ]

472
00:48:17,498 --> 00:48:20,330
They smell even worse
when they burn, don't they?

473
00:48:20,414 --> 00:48:21,497
What?

474
00:48:38,414 --> 00:48:40,121
But, surely you-

475
00:48:55,914 --> 00:48:58,288
Elsa, I was sworn to secrecy.

476
00:48:58,414 --> 00:49:00,621
From your own wife.
Yes.

477
00:49:04,789 --> 00:49:09,080
I took an oath upon my life.
Do you understand?

478
00:49:10,705 --> 00:49:14,455
Elsa, you believe in this, too.

479
00:49:14,539 --> 00:49:19,455
- You want this country to be strong-
- No, Ralf, no! No, not that!

480
00:49:24,164 --> 00:49:25,579
How can you-

481
00:49:25,705 --> 00:49:27,330
Because I'm a soldier.
How can you-

482
00:49:27,414 --> 00:49:30,163
- Soldiers fight wars.
- That isn't war!

483
00:49:30,247 --> 00:49:32,954
It's a part of it! It's a vital part of it!

484
00:49:34,456 --> 00:49:38,455
The Fatherland we all desire,
all of us, you included,

485
00:49:38,538 --> 00:49:41,372
cannot be achieved without work such as this!

486
00:49:41,456 --> 00:49:44,038
[ Sobbing ]

487
00:49:44,164 --> 00:49:49,497
Elsa. Elsa.
Get away from me! Get away from me!

488
00:49:50,498 --> 00:49:52,663
[ Sobbing ]

489
00:49:53,705 --> 00:49:54,871
Grandpa's here.

490
00:49:54,955 --> 00:49:56,954
I don't believe this.
Grandpa's here.

491
00:50:01,247 --> 00:50:02,496
We'll be through in a moment.

492
00:50:13,331 --> 00:50:14,455
Who told you about this?

493
00:50:47,164 --> 00:50:49,163
How's Grandma?

494
00:50:49,247 --> 00:50:51,704
She's a bit under the weather, I'm afraid.

495
00:50:51,789 --> 00:50:56,246
It's a shame, she was so much
looking forward to seeing you.

496
00:50:56,373 --> 00:50:59,413
Perhaps next time, if she feels up to it.
Oh, absolutely.

497
00:51:06,289 --> 00:51:10,871
You know, Ralf, your mother really is sick.

498
00:51:11,872 --> 00:51:14,537
She's been talking about this visit for weeks.

499
00:51:14,622 --> 00:51:16,788
Maybe that's what's made her sick.

500
00:51:23,747 --> 00:51:26,788
[ Grandpa ]
So, your father tells me
that you've got a tutor.

501
00:51:27,580 --> 00:51:29,829
Yes. He's nice.

502
00:51:29,914 --> 00:51:32,579
[ Bruno ]
But he won't let us read
any adventure books.

503
00:51:33,455 --> 00:51:35,788
All we do is boring, old history.

504
00:51:35,872 --> 00:51:38,330
[ Chuckles ]
Let me tell you something, young man.

505
00:51:38,413 --> 00:51:42,246
If it wasn't for history, we wouldn't
all be sitting around this table.

506
00:51:42,997 --> 00:51:45,621
The work your father is doing here,

507
00:51:46,664 --> 00:51:48,829
history in the making.

508
00:51:59,122 --> 00:52:02,663
When I was your age, history was
my favorite subject by miles,

509
00:52:02,747 --> 00:52:04,829
which obviously didn't please my father.

510
00:52:04,914 --> 00:52:06,788
Why not?

511
00:52:06,872 --> 00:52:09,829
Well, he was a professor of literature
at the university.

512
00:52:09,914 --> 00:52:13,788
[ Grandpa ]
Really, does he still teach?

513
00:52:16,247 --> 00:52:19,746
- I don't really know.
- You don't know?

514
00:52:22,705 --> 00:52:27,371
We're not in touch, my father and I.
He left the country some time ago.

515
00:52:29,955 --> 00:52:31,621
Really, when?

516
00:52:33,789 --> 00:52:37,080
About four years ago, Herr Kommandant.

517
00:52:40,622 --> 00:52:45,080
But surely he can't be very old.
What is he, still in his 40s, late 40s?

518
00:52:45,914 --> 00:52:46,996
Where did he go?

519
00:52:55,538 --> 00:52:57,246
Lieutenant Kotler,

520
00:52:58,580 --> 00:53:02,121
your father, the professor of literature,
where did he go?

521
00:53:07,955 --> 00:53:10,996
I believe it was Switzerland, Herr Kommandant.

522
00:53:12,330 --> 00:53:14,704
How strange that he should choose
to leave the Fatherland...

523
00:53:14,789 --> 00:53:16,704
at the very moment it needed him most.

524
00:53:16,789 --> 00:53:19,163
Just when we're all required
to play our part in the national revival.

525
00:53:19,247 --> 00:53:20,621
More wine!

526
00:53:23,039 --> 00:53:25,788
What reason did he give?
Was he tubercular?

527
00:53:25,872 --> 00:53:26,579
Herr Kommandant?

528
00:53:28,747 --> 00:53:30,329
Did he go there to take the air?

529
00:53:32,955 --> 00:53:34,746
I'm afraid I really don't know, Herr Kommandant.

530
00:53:34,830 --> 00:53:36,788
You'd have to ask him.

531
00:53:36,872 --> 00:53:39,579
Well, that would be rather difficult,
wouldn't it?

532
00:53:39,664 --> 00:53:41,788
With him being in Switzerland.

533
00:53:42,622 --> 00:53:43,663
Come on!

534
00:53:45,081 --> 00:53:47,621
What's the matter with you tonight?

535
00:53:55,789 --> 00:54:00,788
Yes, perhaps that was it.
Perhaps he was ill.

536
00:54:02,789 --> 00:54:05,121
Unless, of course, he had disagreements.

537
00:54:07,413 --> 00:54:11,245
- I mean, with government policy.
- [ Grandpa ] One hears of such men.

538
00:54:11,330 --> 00:54:15,579
Disturbed, most of them, or just plain cowards.

539
00:54:15,705 --> 00:54:19,371
Even so, all of them traitors.
Absolutely right.

540
00:54:19,455 --> 00:54:23,704
Presumably,
if that was the case with your father,

541
00:54:23,789 --> 00:54:27,496
you will have informed your superiors,
as is your duty.

542
00:54:29,622 --> 00:54:30,829
Lieutenant Kotler!

543
00:54:32,246 --> 00:54:35,287
You cretin Jew! Filth!

544
00:54:36,246 --> 00:54:39,454
[ Groaning ]
[ Kicks Landing ]

545
00:54:40,747 --> 00:54:42,954
[ Groaning ]
[ Grunting ]

546
00:54:45,081 --> 00:54:46,954
[ Grunting ]
Pig!

547
00:54:47,039 --> 00:54:48,287
Ralf!

548
00:54:50,914 --> 00:54:53,371
[ Grunting ]

549
00:54:53,455 --> 00:54:54,704
Jew!

550
00:54:55,872 --> 00:54:59,704
- But Dad just sat there.
- What did you expect him to do?

551
00:54:59,789 --> 00:55:00,954
The Jew deserved it.

552
00:55:10,622 --> 00:55:14,454
Can I ask you something about the farm?

553
00:55:14,538 --> 00:55:17,454
Bruno, you don't still think it's a farm,
do you?

554
00:55:36,288 --> 00:55:40,162
It's a camp.
What's called a work camp.

555
00:55:40,246 --> 00:55:42,746
For Jews, obviously.

556
00:55:44,288 --> 00:55:46,080
Just Jews?

557
00:55:46,955 --> 00:55:49,788
Because they're the best workers?

558
00:55:49,872 --> 00:55:51,537
They're not in there
because they're good, silly.

559
00:55:51,622 --> 00:55:53,788
They're no good at anything.

560
00:55:53,872 --> 00:55:55,412
They're in there because they're evil.

561
00:55:55,538 --> 00:55:57,829
They're the enemy.
The enemy?

562
00:55:57,955 --> 00:55:59,829
But I thought we were fighting-
They're evil, Bruno.

563
00:55:59,914 --> 00:56:02,287
Evil, dangerous vermin.

564
00:56:02,955 --> 00:56:04,663
They're the reason we lost the Great War.

565
00:56:05,789 --> 00:56:09,746
Haven't you been listening to anything
Herr Liszt has been telling us?

566
00:56:09,830 --> 00:56:11,245
No. Not really.

567
00:56:14,122 --> 00:56:17,287
Dad's not horrible, is he?
He's a good man.

568
00:56:17,413 --> 00:56:21,996
Of course, he is.
But he's in charge of a horrible place.

569
00:56:22,081 --> 00:56:24,704
It's only horrible for them, Bruno.

570
00:56:24,789 --> 00:56:27,287
We should be proud of Dad,
now more than ever before.

571
00:56:27,372 --> 00:56:29,996
He's making the country great again.

572
00:57:22,121 --> 00:57:25,329
[ Elsa ]
Like you say, they're a bit strange.
A bit-

573
00:57:25,413 --> 00:57:26,454
Well, they're different.

574
00:57:26,538 --> 00:57:28,537
[ Gretel ]
They're the enemy, Bruno.

575
00:57:28,622 --> 00:57:30,329
Evil, dangerous vermin.

576
00:57:30,413 --> 00:57:33,621
[ Ralf]
Well, you see,
they're not really people at all.

577
00:57:40,163 --> 00:57:43,287
[ Chattering ]

578
00:57:57,622 --> 00:58:00,037
What are you doing here?

579
00:58:00,121 --> 00:58:04,287
They wanted someone with tiny fingers
to clean all these.

580
00:58:17,163 --> 00:58:20,204
We're not supposed to be friends, you and me.

581
00:58:20,288 --> 00:58:23,245
We're meant to be enemies.
Did you know that?

582
00:58:30,288 --> 00:58:31,954
Do you want some?

583
00:58:42,455 --> 00:58:45,079
What's your dad like?
What's he like?

584
00:58:45,580 --> 00:58:47,204
Is he a good man?

585
00:58:50,121 --> 00:58:51,913
You've never thought he wasn't?

586
00:58:55,080 --> 00:58:57,120
And you're proud of him?

587
00:58:58,455 --> 00:59:00,496
Aren't you proud of yours?

588
00:59:04,872 --> 00:59:06,579
Is it really horrible in the camp?

589
00:59:07,996 --> 00:59:09,953
How dare you talk to people in the house.

590
00:59:10,038 --> 00:59:12,287
How dare you!

591
00:59:14,789 --> 00:59:16,329
Are you eating?

592
00:59:18,914 --> 00:59:21,079
Have you been stealing food?

593
00:59:24,914 --> 00:59:29,204
Answer me!
No, sir. He gave it to me.

594
00:59:29,872 --> 00:59:30,995
He's my friend.

595
00:59:33,747 --> 00:59:35,120
What?

596
00:59:37,747 --> 00:59:38,621
Little man,

597
00:59:40,954 --> 00:59:43,120
do you know this Jew?

598
00:59:43,205 --> 00:59:44,829
Do you know this Jew?

599
00:59:44,913 --> 00:59:47,788
No, I just walked in,
and he was helping himself.

600
00:59:48,246 --> 00:59:51,245
I've never seen him before in my life.

601
00:59:59,913 --> 01:00:02,412
You, finish cleaning the glasses.

602
01:00:03,789 --> 01:00:05,412
When I come back, we'll have a little chat...

603
01:00:05,497 --> 01:00:09,329
about what happens to rats who steal.
Come away.

604
01:00:27,121 --> 01:00:29,329
[ Grunts ]

605
01:01:12,538 --> 01:01:15,079
[ Dog Barking ]

606
01:01:50,871 --> 01:01:53,371
[ Man Narrating ]
New arrivals here are happy
to discover that life in the camp...

607
01:01:53,455 --> 01:01:54,579
is not all work.

608
01:01:54,664 --> 01:01:57,953
And that there's
ample opportunity for leisure also.

609
01:01:58,038 --> 01:02:00,412
At the end of their day at the ironmongery...

610
01:02:00,497 --> 01:02:03,037
or the build or boot factory,
the workers can enjoy...

611
01:02:03,121 --> 01:02:06,454
the many forms of pastime
that the camp has to offer.

612
01:02:07,372 --> 01:02:10,079
Organized sport is very popular.

613
01:02:10,163 --> 01:02:13,245
Those that don't play certainly enjoy watching.

614
01:02:15,330 --> 01:02:16,746
At the end of the working day,

615
01:02:16,829 --> 01:02:19,204
the centrally located café is the ideal place...

616
01:02:19,288 --> 01:02:23,870
for friends and families to join together
for a hearty and nutritious meal.

617
01:02:24,580 --> 01:02:28,746
The children, in particular,
enjoy the pastries and cakes on offer.

618
01:02:34,246 --> 01:02:36,787
In the evenings, the occasional music concerts,

619
01:02:36,871 --> 01:02:39,870
either by visiting orchestras
or, indeed, by talented musicians...

620
01:02:39,954 --> 01:02:42,787
from within the camp itself,
are always well attended.

621
01:02:45,080 --> 01:02:47,537
Other recreations include
reading in the library,

622
01:02:47,622 --> 01:02:53,496
pottery, cookery, art and horticulture
for adult and child alike.

623
01:02:53,580 --> 01:02:57,745
Almost any activity one could wish for
is available within the camp.

624
01:03:03,746 --> 01:03:04,621
Splendid.

625
01:03:15,121 --> 01:03:17,120
[ Man ]
Bravo. Excellent.
[ Dad ] Thank you.

626
01:04:03,788 --> 01:04:04,953
Good-bye, little man.

627
01:04:52,288 --> 01:04:54,120
Shmuel! Shmuel!

628
01:05:11,288 --> 01:05:13,371
I don't understand.

629
01:05:13,455 --> 01:05:15,953
I saw a film about the camp,

630
01:05:17,288 --> 01:05:19,204
and it looked so nice.

631
01:05:26,621 --> 01:05:28,620
I don't know why I did it.

632
01:05:29,038 --> 01:05:31,787
Gretel and everyone
were saying all these things,

633
01:05:31,871 --> 01:05:34,037
and that soldier's so scary.

634
01:05:39,330 --> 01:05:42,953
Been coming here for days,
but you were never here.

635
01:05:43,038 --> 01:05:47,870
I thought maybe we weren't friends anymore.

636
01:05:56,288 --> 01:06:00,662
Shmuel, I'm really sorry for what I did.
We are still friends, aren't we?

637
01:06:20,372 --> 01:06:22,787
[ Phone Rings ]

638
01:06:32,205 --> 01:06:35,662
Where's Kurt these days?
I haven't seen him for ages.

639
01:06:37,163 --> 01:06:40,953
- Who's Kurt?
- Lieutenant Kotler.

640
01:06:42,621 --> 01:06:44,953
He's been moved to the front.

641
01:06:45,038 --> 01:06:46,912
It was felt that his youth and enthusiasm...

642
01:06:46,996 --> 01:06:48,745
would be put to better use there.

643
01:06:48,829 --> 01:06:50,953
Herr Kommandant, telephone.

644
01:06:51,871 --> 01:06:54,371
In actual fact, Gretel, he was sent there...

645
01:06:54,455 --> 01:06:56,204
because he failed to inform the authorities...

646
01:06:56,288 --> 01:06:58,536
of his father's lack of loyalty to the Party.

647
01:06:58,621 --> 01:07:00,578
Which was his duty, I might add.

648
01:07:00,663 --> 01:07:02,745
Which was his bad luck.
Bad luck?

649
01:07:02,829 --> 01:07:06,912
Well, bad luck that it was his father
who was disloyal, and not his mother.

650
01:07:06,996 --> 01:07:09,828
One presumably
doesn't have to report one's mother.

651
01:07:15,288 --> 01:07:17,828
What?
When will Pavel be back?

652
01:07:20,038 --> 01:07:23,079
- Mum?
- Never, stupid.

653
01:07:27,788 --> 01:07:29,662
It's Father. They've been bombed.

654
01:07:35,496 --> 01:07:36,495
Grandmother's dead.

655
01:07:53,038 --> 01:07:55,620
[ Bell Tolls ]

656
01:08:22,579 --> 01:08:25,245
"...the victory
which You have obtained for us...

657
01:08:25,330 --> 01:08:27,620
and for all who sleep in Him,

658
01:08:27,704 --> 01:08:31,287
keep us who are still in the body
in everlasting fellowship...

659
01:08:31,372 --> 01:08:33,371
with all that wait for Thee on earth,

660
01:08:33,454 --> 01:08:36,204
and with all that are around Thee in heaven,

661
01:08:36,288 --> 01:08:38,578
in union with Him who is the resurrection...

662
01:08:38,663 --> 01:08:42,371
and the life, who liveth and reigneth
with Thee and the Holy Ghost,

663
01:08:42,454 --> 01:08:45,536
ever one God, world without end.
Amen."

664
01:08:45,621 --> 01:08:48,079
He can't have that on there.
She wouldn't have wanted it.

665
01:08:50,371 --> 01:08:52,120
He does.

666
01:09:19,412 --> 01:09:21,120
[ Minister Continues ]
"Almighty God, who by the death of-"

667
01:09:21,205 --> 01:09:22,578
[ Bruno ]
Have you ever been to a funeral?

668
01:09:24,496 --> 01:09:27,912
My grandma and grandpa both died
just after we got here,

669
01:09:27,996 --> 01:09:30,287
but there weren't any funerals.

670
01:09:32,704 --> 01:09:34,870
That one there to there.

671
01:09:38,121 --> 01:09:39,912
They both died at the same time?

672
01:09:40,954 --> 01:09:42,162
What of?

673
01:09:43,663 --> 01:09:44,745
I don't know.

674
01:09:44,829 --> 01:09:47,787
Papa said they must have caught
something on the way here.

675
01:09:48,788 --> 01:09:51,162
They had to go to a hospital
as soon as we arrived.

676
01:09:51,996 --> 01:09:54,037
We didn't see them again.

677
01:09:57,788 --> 01:09:59,620
[ Sighs ]
This is fun.

678
01:10:00,663 --> 01:10:04,162
Wish we could do something
a bit more exciting, though.

679
01:10:08,163 --> 01:10:11,620
- That one there to there.
- This one?

680
01:10:13,704 --> 01:10:15,411
- This one?
- No, that one.

681
01:10:16,496 --> 01:10:19,204
- This one to here?
- No, there!

682
01:10:19,287 --> 01:10:21,411
- To here?
- No.

683
01:10:21,496 --> 01:10:22,703
- Here?
- No.

684
01:10:22,788 --> 01:10:26,079
[ Giggling ]

685
01:10:30,954 --> 01:10:36,286
- I don't want you to go away again.
- No. Neither do I.

686
01:11:04,537 --> 01:11:06,620
[ Ralf]
You can't behave like this!

687
01:11:07,329 --> 01:11:10,745
[ Elsa ]
You're questioning my behavior?
It can't continue!

688
01:11:10,829 --> 01:11:13,620
I know.
I can't stand this anymore, Ralf.

689
01:11:13,704 --> 01:11:15,787
I can't stay here and be a part of this.

690
01:11:17,121 --> 01:11:18,870
Don't you think there will be questions?

691
01:11:18,996 --> 01:11:20,411
Questions?
Well, now, what does it say...

692
01:11:20,496 --> 01:11:25,162
about my ability to carry out my work
if I cannot control my own family?

693
01:11:25,287 --> 01:11:28,204
Work? Is that what you call it?
Pull yourself together, woman.

694
01:11:28,287 --> 01:11:30,037
Right.Just ignore it. Ignore it.

695
01:11:30,121 --> 01:11:34,079
Ignore the fact that
the man I married is a monster!

696
01:11:34,163 --> 01:11:36,453
Even your own mother couldn't love you.

697
01:11:46,537 --> 01:11:48,286
Are you happy here?

698
01:11:49,704 --> 01:11:51,453
Yes. Very.

699
01:11:54,663 --> 01:11:56,286
And you, Gretel?

700
01:11:58,121 --> 01:12:03,787
Well, I was, but I do miss home.
I miss my friends.

701
01:12:04,287 --> 01:12:09,120
Yes, I'm sure. And you, too, Bruno.
You must miss those friends of yours.

702
01:12:10,287 --> 01:12:12,953
No. Not anymore, really.

703
01:12:24,704 --> 01:12:30,203
I suppose the real question is,
if the opportunity arose,

704
01:12:31,621 --> 01:12:33,912
would you prefer to live somewhere else?

705
01:12:33,996 --> 01:12:37,870
[ Gretel ] Back home?
No. Not Berlin. Not yet.

706
01:12:38,454 --> 01:12:43,995
Somewhere safe, say Aunt Lottie's
in Heidelberg, for example.

707
01:12:44,788 --> 01:12:46,912
All of us? You as well?

708
01:12:48,121 --> 01:12:51,370
No. That won't be possible just yet,
I'm afraid.

709
01:12:51,454 --> 01:12:54,037
I must stay and complete my work here.

710
01:12:56,454 --> 01:13:00,119
See, at the moment,
your mother is finding it-

711
01:13:02,329 --> 01:13:06,536
She just feels right now you need
to spend some time elsewhere.

712
01:13:06,621 --> 01:13:08,453
Would you like that?

713
01:13:18,454 --> 01:13:23,912
I'm afraid, Bruno, in life, we often
have to do things we don't want to do.

714
01:13:23,996 --> 01:13:26,703
The important thing is
your mother does not feel...

715
01:13:26,788 --> 01:13:29,620
that this is an appropriate place for you
to be spending your childhood,

716
01:13:29,704 --> 01:13:33,370
and the more I think about it, the more
I realize she's very probably right.

717
01:13:33,454 --> 01:13:35,161
- But, Dad-
- No!

718
01:13:41,996 --> 01:13:44,286
It's time for you to move away.

719
01:14:09,454 --> 01:14:11,411
Is everything all right?

720
01:14:14,371 --> 01:14:16,244
We can't find Papa.

721
01:14:16,329 --> 01:14:18,953
He went on a different work duty
with some of the men,

722
01:14:19,037 --> 01:14:21,078
and they haven't come back.

723
01:14:30,287 --> 01:14:33,953
I've got some bad news, too.
I'm going away.

724
01:14:35,704 --> 01:14:37,620
How long for this time?

725
01:14:38,120 --> 01:14:41,620
That's why it's bad.
It's forever, I think.

726
01:14:42,704 --> 01:14:47,036
Mum says this is no place for children,
which is just stupid.

727
01:14:47,537 --> 01:14:50,703
When do you go?
Tomorrow. After lunch.

728
01:14:51,829 --> 01:14:56,620
So, I won't ever see you again?

729
01:14:58,496 --> 01:15:02,578
Yes, you will. You can come on holiday
to Berlin if you like,

730
01:15:02,663 --> 01:15:06,078
when everybody's getting on
with each other again.

731
01:15:10,704 --> 01:15:13,161
I wish I could've helped you find your dad.

732
01:15:14,204 --> 01:15:17,703
I really want to make up
for letting you down like I did.

733
01:15:17,788 --> 01:15:20,745
That would have done it, wouldn't it?
Helping you find your dad?

734
01:15:20,829 --> 01:15:23,662
Would've been great.
Like a secret mission.

735
01:15:28,537 --> 01:15:31,828
I could dig under.
What? With that?

736
01:15:31,954 --> 01:15:35,620
No, but I could bring something.
You don't want to come over here.

737
01:15:39,704 --> 01:15:40,787
Look.

738
01:15:47,371 --> 01:15:50,703
I could come through to your side.
What's the point in that?

739
01:15:50,788 --> 01:15:53,620
Your dad's not going to be over here, is he?

740
01:15:54,204 --> 01:15:58,203
But I'd stick out though, wouldn't I,
if I came through?

741
01:15:58,287 --> 01:16:00,161
I don't look like you.

742
01:16:00,245 --> 01:16:03,161
[ Whistle Blows ]

743
01:16:03,871 --> 01:16:05,952
You could look like me, though.

744
01:16:06,037 --> 01:16:08,370
If you dressed like me and shaved your hair off.

745
01:16:08,454 --> 01:16:10,495
I'm not shaving my hair off.

746
01:16:10,621 --> 01:16:15,036
You could cover it with a cap.
My pajamas are a different color.

747
01:16:15,120 --> 01:16:18,662
I could bring some.
There's a hut full of them,

748
01:16:18,746 --> 01:16:21,495
thousands of them.
Would you do it, though?

749
01:16:21,579 --> 01:16:23,994
- I want to do it.
- Would you dare do it, though?

750
01:16:24,079 --> 01:16:26,536
- I want to help you find your dad.
- I've got to go.

751
01:16:26,621 --> 01:16:30,036
Tomorrow, then?
I'll bring an extra-big sandwich.

752
01:16:30,120 --> 01:16:32,286
And don't forget the pajamas!

753
01:17:35,245 --> 01:17:36,411
Bruno?

754
01:17:37,120 --> 01:17:40,952
Mum, can I go and play on the swing?

755
01:17:42,329 --> 01:17:45,078
- Bruno-
- It's my last chance.

756
01:17:46,704 --> 01:17:49,119
[ Sighs ]
All right. Go on then.

757
01:18:20,412 --> 01:18:24,662
I thought you weren't coming!
I'm sorry. It wasn't easy to get away.

758
01:18:24,746 --> 01:18:28,411
I'm not meant to be out here today.
You forgot the pajamas!

759
01:18:30,245 --> 01:18:33,411
- Did you bring the sandwich?
- Would I let you down?

760
01:18:35,454 --> 01:18:36,952
Oh.

761
01:18:58,287 --> 01:18:59,495
Shmuel.

762
01:19:08,287 --> 01:19:09,411
Here.

763
01:19:11,663 --> 01:19:13,328
[ Whistle Tweets In Distance ]

764
01:19:24,953 --> 01:19:25,952
How do I look?

765
01:19:27,745 --> 01:19:29,952
[ Thunder Cracks ]

766
01:19:33,995 --> 01:19:35,952
Right. Let's get going.

767
01:19:52,245 --> 01:19:53,411
Bruno?

768
01:19:54,787 --> 01:19:56,286
[ Bruno ]
That's enough.

769
01:20:17,745 --> 01:20:20,411
[ Giggles ]

770
01:20:21,162 --> 01:20:22,952
[ Giggles ]

771
01:20:26,496 --> 01:20:28,286
Let's go and find your dad.

772
01:20:33,995 --> 01:20:35,244
Come on!

773
01:20:35,745 --> 01:20:37,328
Master Bruno?

774
01:20:49,245 --> 01:20:51,453
[ Dogs Barking ]

775
01:21:22,079 --> 01:21:23,286
[ Bruno ]
Shmuel.

776
01:21:24,079 --> 01:21:26,952
Can we go to the café or something?
Café?

777
01:21:30,579 --> 01:21:33,744
- Maybe I should go home.
- What about Papa?

778
01:21:43,287 --> 01:21:44,411
Yeah.

779
01:21:47,912 --> 01:21:50,119
We'll check our hut first.

780
01:21:53,787 --> 01:21:55,328
Bruno?

781
01:22:02,745 --> 01:22:04,244
Come on.

782
01:22:09,787 --> 01:22:12,911
[ Flies Buzzing ]

783
01:22:17,079 --> 01:22:18,078
Papa?

784
01:22:20,787 --> 01:22:22,869
[ Man Shouting ]
Up! Up! Get up!

785
01:22:22,995 --> 01:22:25,036
What's happening?
I don't know.

786
01:22:25,120 --> 01:22:26,869
We go on marches sometimes.

787
01:22:26,953 --> 01:22:28,952
[ Man ]
Move! Up, up!

788
01:22:31,120 --> 01:22:32,911
Move, move!

789
01:22:35,578 --> 01:22:38,328
[ Man Shouting, Indistinct ]

790
01:22:43,620 --> 01:22:45,286
[ Elsa ]
Bruno!

791
01:22:46,245 --> 01:22:48,411
[ Maria ]
He must still be
outside somewhere, ma'am.

792
01:23:01,204 --> 01:23:03,078
[ Thunder Rumbling ]

793
01:23:03,162 --> 01:23:04,786
Bruno!

794
01:23:07,536 --> 01:23:08,786
Bruno?

795
01:23:20,329 --> 01:23:22,370
Move!
Quickly!

796
01:23:22,454 --> 01:23:25,328
[ Groaning ]

797
01:23:25,412 --> 01:23:26,786
Get up!

798
01:23:29,329 --> 01:23:31,119
[ Man Murmurs ]
Get up. You must!

799
01:23:32,287 --> 01:23:33,744
Move them out!

800
01:23:37,703 --> 01:23:40,078
[ Gunshot ]

801
01:23:45,412 --> 01:23:47,661
[ Ralf]
...which means that
our weekly capabilities...

802
01:23:47,745 --> 01:23:49,244
would be almost tripled,

803
01:23:49,329 --> 01:23:51,577
so, therefore,
by the end of the summer-

804
01:23:51,662 --> 01:23:54,786
- Ralf.
- Elsa, I'm in a meeting.

805
01:23:55,412 --> 01:23:56,453
Bruno's missing.

806
01:24:02,745 --> 01:24:04,078
Come on!

807
01:24:10,745 --> 01:24:12,411
Wait here!

808
01:24:23,245 --> 01:24:24,577
Come on!

809
01:24:27,453 --> 01:24:28,786
[ Man ]
Move! Move!

810
01:24:36,787 --> 01:24:38,411
Join the queue!

811
01:24:44,912 --> 01:24:46,494
[ Panting ]

812
01:24:46,578 --> 01:24:47,952
[ Man ]
Come on, you!

813
01:24:48,037 --> 01:24:49,952
[ Thunder Cracks ]

814
01:24:57,120 --> 01:24:58,661
Bruno!

815
01:24:59,329 --> 01:25:00,952
Move it!

816
01:25:03,620 --> 01:25:05,119
Go on.

817
01:25:06,703 --> 01:25:08,203
Bruno!

818
01:25:08,287 --> 01:25:10,869
[ Chattering ]

819
01:25:17,828 --> 01:25:22,702
It's all right. I think we're just waiting
in here until the rain stops.

820
01:25:22,787 --> 01:25:24,161
[ Man ]
Clothes off!

821
01:25:24,245 --> 01:25:25,786
[ Men Murmuring ]

822
01:25:32,329 --> 01:25:34,328
Where are we going?

823
01:25:38,912 --> 01:25:40,494
No, it's just a shower.

824
01:25:42,287 --> 01:25:44,161
A shower?

825
01:25:52,870 --> 01:25:54,952
Herr Kommandant!

826
01:26:17,037 --> 01:26:20,619
[ Men Chattering Loudly ]

827
01:26:32,787 --> 01:26:35,452
Open the gates! Open the gates!

828
01:26:37,703 --> 01:26:39,036
[ Indistinct ]

829
01:26:39,120 --> 01:26:40,244
Move!

830
01:26:56,245 --> 01:26:58,661
[ Murmuring ]

831
01:27:03,745 --> 01:27:06,078
[ Shouting ]

832
01:27:13,995 --> 01:27:17,452
[ Shouting ]

833
01:27:17,536 --> 01:27:20,452
[ Banging ]

834
01:27:22,453 --> 01:27:23,786
Move!

835
01:27:24,870 --> 01:27:27,119
[ Dogs Barking ]

836
01:27:31,495 --> 01:27:35,327
[ Flies Buzzing ]

837
01:27:40,828 --> 01:27:43,369
[ No Sound ]

838
01:27:58,370 --> 01:28:00,036
Bruno!

839
01:28:00,120 --> 01:28:03,078
[ Voice Echoing ]

840
01:28:14,662 --> 01:28:20,619
[ Sobbing, Screaming ]

841
01:28:29,620 --> 01:28:33,243
[ Screaming ]

